In these 13 wine properties, 11 of them are quantitative and 1 is ordered factor(quality).

From the quality histogram I can see that even its rated from 0-10, but this dataset only having wine with quality

from 3-9 with a median 6 and 95% falls into 5-7

Since most value are greater than 0 theres few plot have skewness in it.

Theres still outliers on chlorides this case Ill limit x-scale

From this plot, theres clear upward trend in alcohol/quality, not that clear downtrend on density/quality & chlorides/quality.

Adding a liner model to the jitter plot here

These line overall reprensented the trend here that the higher alcohol volumn have higher quality level, the higher density have a lower quality and the higher chlorides also results to a lower quality level.

Also, besides the feature we interested in, we can also see some other releationshp between other attributes from the ggpair plot.

  1. Density/Residual.Sugar: 0.825

  3. Density/Alcohol: -0.806

Ill also using scatter point plot to investigate these varibles.

Here we can see since theres very strong correlations, the line fit very well here. Higher residual suglar result higher density, higher alcohol volumn leads to lower density, and as for non free sulfur dioxide its a part of total sulfur dioxide so its shows positive correlation.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

From the plot I have aboive, the quality varible is correlated with alcohol & density & chlorides. As alcohol level increase, the quality level also trending upwards, while density & chlorides increasing, the quality trending downwards. However the correlation between these variable is not strong enough to fit into a linear model as I tried above

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features

I found that alcohol & density have a strong negetive correlation, while alcohol increasing, then density trending downwards, this is also reflected in the quality plot.

Also the residual.sugar have strong positive correlation with density, this is very reasonable since sugar (1.59 g/cm) in general have a bigger density than water(1 g/cm) & ethanol (0.79 g/cm), hence more sugar left the the bigger density the wine will have.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest correlation I found will be non.free.sulfur.dioxide & total.sulfur.dioxide, this is due to one variable is a subset of another, so it will always be a very strong correlation.

Multivariate Plots Section

Here Ill try to seperate quality into bigger bucket as bad/normal/good by seperating buckets,

Also as I learned before the residual.sugar is bimodal, seperating as low/high by median value.

In this set of plot, its clearly shows the releationship between each 3 variables, Plot#1 as alcohol level increase, the quality also increasing and density dropped. Plot#2 here I can see the bad grade mostly associate wiht higher chlorides and the good wine have a lower chlorides. Plot#3 shows that good grade wine will have a smaller density & residual.sugar amount.

This set of plot shows the relationship of the core 3 variable with residual.sugar. Higher residual.sugar have highr density and lower alcohol,lower chlorides, vise versa.

Using lm function build liner model with the 3 big correlation variables:

Reflection

From this project, I learned how to do explory data analysis first time, from raw data,histogram,boxplot,changing axis to box plot, removing outlier and all the way to multi-variable plot. While during the process, I feel like its really hard to find a perfect model for this dataset to predicting wine quality, none of these variable have a strong correlation directy. Also theres many variable to choose from and this make me feel a lot of uncertainty. Although I tried to fit it into a linear model but its certainly not the best fit. I would hope if we have more variable avaialble to have direct or indirect releations. Also if quality is not discrete by numbers more like have decimal to 0.01 I feel like the plot will have better visuilization.Theres also space to be improved here in this analysis as I can try to make new varible using exisitng one, to see if a better correlation existing.

Overall I feel like doing real data analysing could be more harder, theres always be hidden relationship/variables that will need to be digged out so we can see the big picture, we will not always see obvious correlation all the time, this will need me to have a set of solution and step by step find every piece of the puzzle. Im looking forward to do more practice like this through kaggle to get more famillar with the methodology.

As for the future work I would like also introduce the red wine dataset into my analysis as a reference gruop to see if all wines have same property/characteristics between these 2 kinds. After introduce red wine data I can have an analysis side by side and overall enrich my dataset to have a better look to confirm the findings that I already found.
